1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,520
INSTRUCTOR: In this final
part of the lecture,

2
00:00:02,520 --> 00:00:07,160
our goal is to identify patients
who benefit from treatment,

3
00:00:07,160 --> 00:00:11,840
but now using interpretable
AI applied directly

4
00:00:11,840 --> 00:00:15,400
to randomized trial data.

5
00:00:15,400 --> 00:00:17,840
This might seem to
contradict the implications

6
00:00:17,840 --> 00:00:22,880
of row two, where we emphasized
the power and flexibility

7
00:00:22,880 --> 00:00:26,000
of using real-world data.

8
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:29,080
So why return to RCTs now?

9
00:00:29,080 --> 00:00:32,299
Because we need to directly
compare our method,

10
00:00:32,299 --> 00:00:35,760
optimal policy trees, to
the current gold standard

11
00:00:35,760 --> 00:00:38,400
for subgroup discovery in RCTs.

12
00:00:38,400 --> 00:00:42,960
The one variable at a
time subgroup analysis.

13
00:00:42,960 --> 00:00:44,760
This is the
conventional approach

14
00:00:44,760 --> 00:00:48,320
where researchers stratify
the RCT population

15
00:00:48,320 --> 00:00:53,400
by individual variables, like
tumor size, age, or biomarker

16
00:00:53,400 --> 00:00:58,160
status, and test whether
the treatment effect differs

17
00:00:58,160 --> 00:01:00,320
across strata.

18
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:05,099
But as we will see next, this
approach has major limitations.

19
00:01:05,099 --> 00:01:09,850
And that's where the power of
interpretable AI really shines.

20
00:01:09,850 --> 00:01:12,900


21
00:01:12,900 --> 00:01:17,660
Let's pause here to contrast the
two approaches, optimal policy

22
00:01:17,660 --> 00:01:22,860
trees versus conventional
subgroup analysis.

23
00:01:22,860 --> 00:01:26,260
A few words on the
conventional approach.

24
00:01:26,260 --> 00:01:31,780
These analyses stratify patients
based on one variable at a time,

25
00:01:31,780 --> 00:01:36,300
say, tumor location,
histologic subtype, or age.

26
00:01:36,300 --> 00:01:41,100
Then they compare treatment
effects within those strata.

27
00:01:41,100 --> 00:01:45,340
For example, older
versus younger patients.

28
00:01:45,340 --> 00:01:47,540
But here is the issue.

29
00:01:47,540 --> 00:01:50,940
Patients don't differ
based on one factor only.

30
00:01:50,940 --> 00:01:53,460
They differ across many.

31
00:01:53,460 --> 00:01:56,420
In addition, when you
test multiple variables

32
00:01:56,420 --> 00:01:59,700
independently, you run
into the classic problem

33
00:01:59,700 --> 00:02:02,940
of multiple hypothesis
testing, which

34
00:02:02,940 --> 00:02:08,270
inflates the risk of
spurious positive findings.

35
00:02:08,270 --> 00:02:10,830
In contrast,
optimal policy trees

36
00:02:10,830 --> 00:02:13,270
do something very different.

37
00:02:13,270 --> 00:02:16,870
They begin by predicting
each patient's outcome

38
00:02:16,870 --> 00:02:19,190
under both treatment scenarios.

39
00:02:19,190 --> 00:02:21,830
For example,
recurrence-free survival

40
00:02:21,830 --> 00:02:25,150
with and without radiotherapy.

41
00:02:25,150 --> 00:02:29,270
These predictions are based
on all available covariates

42
00:02:29,270 --> 00:02:33,270
in a counterfactual
model, not just one.

43
00:02:33,270 --> 00:02:36,870
Then, these predictions are
used to train a decision

44
00:02:36,870 --> 00:02:42,430
tree that groups patients based
on similar treatment benefit,

45
00:02:42,430 --> 00:02:45,150
or lack thereof.

46
00:02:45,150 --> 00:02:49,870
What is powerful here is that
OPTs can identify combinations

47
00:02:49,870 --> 00:02:53,750
of clinical features that
drive benefit, rather than just

48
00:02:53,750 --> 00:02:55,620
flagging a single variable.

49
00:02:55,620 --> 00:02:58,830


50
00:02:58,830 --> 00:03:02,630
To compare the performance of
conventional subgroup analysis

51
00:03:02,630 --> 00:03:05,870
and optimal policy
trees, let me walk you

52
00:03:05,870 --> 00:03:08,310
through a clinical example.

53
00:03:08,310 --> 00:03:14,290
We're looking at retroperitoneal
sarcoma, RPS, a rare cancer

54
00:03:14,290 --> 00:03:20,890
that accounts for about 15%
of all soft tissue sarcomas.

55
00:03:20,890 --> 00:03:23,810
The primary
treatment is surgery,

56
00:03:23,810 --> 00:03:26,290
but there is
ongoing debate about

57
00:03:26,290 --> 00:03:32,610
whether preoperative radiation
therapy, or RT, should be added.

58
00:03:32,610 --> 00:03:39,810
Because RPS is so rare, no RCT
had been conducted for decades.

59
00:03:39,810 --> 00:03:46,170
So for years, investigators
relied on real-world data.

60
00:03:46,170 --> 00:03:50,130
One highly cited RWD study,
published in The Lancet

61
00:03:50,130 --> 00:03:53,530
Oncology, used
propensity score matching

62
00:03:53,530 --> 00:03:56,330
and other rigorous methods.

63
00:03:56,330 --> 00:04:00,610
They found a strong
association between RT

64
00:04:00,610 --> 00:04:05,330
and improved recurrence-free
and overall survival.

65
00:04:05,330 --> 00:04:10,690
But in 2020, the STRASS
trial, the first and only RCT

66
00:04:10,690 --> 00:04:13,130
in this setting, was published.

67
00:04:13,130 --> 00:04:18,500
It found no benefit
from adding radiation.

68
00:04:18,500 --> 00:04:22,540
The discrepancy between the
RWD and the RCT findings

69
00:04:22,540 --> 00:04:26,500
raised a fundamental issue
we have mentioned before.

70
00:04:26,500 --> 00:04:30,660
Even with the best methods,
observational studies cannot

71
00:04:30,660 --> 00:04:34,740
fully address
unobserved confounding.

72
00:04:34,740 --> 00:04:37,460
That, along with
possible differences

73
00:04:37,460 --> 00:04:41,620
in inclusion criteria, likely
explains the conflicting

74
00:04:41,620 --> 00:04:43,220
results.

75
00:04:43,220 --> 00:04:45,270
Back to STRASS.

76
00:04:45,270 --> 00:04:48,900
In an attempt to find
treatment-responsive subgroups

77
00:04:48,900 --> 00:04:52,780
in this overall negative
trial, the investigators

78
00:04:52,780 --> 00:04:55,140
performed conventional
one variable

79
00:04:55,140 --> 00:04:58,580
at a time subgroup analysis.

80
00:04:58,580 --> 00:05:03,180
They reported benefit in
certain histologic subtypes,

81
00:05:03,180 --> 00:05:07,500
but these results were
immediately challenged.

82
00:05:07,500 --> 00:05:12,300
Letters to the editor pointed
out the risk of false positives

83
00:05:12,300 --> 00:05:14,900
due to multiple testing.

84
00:05:14,900 --> 00:05:19,440
Others cited these subgroup
results as a justification

85
00:05:19,440 --> 00:05:22,440
to use RT in clinical practice.

86
00:05:22,440 --> 00:05:24,310
The debate turned chaotic.

87
00:05:24,310 --> 00:05:27,440


88
00:05:27,440 --> 00:05:30,200
We applied optimal
policy trees directly

89
00:05:30,200 --> 00:05:33,880
within the STRASS RCT data set.

90
00:05:33,880 --> 00:05:37,000
So unlike in previous
parts of this lecture,

91
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,080
nothing confounding was needed.

92
00:05:39,080 --> 00:05:42,320
This was randomized data.

93
00:05:42,320 --> 00:05:44,880
But here is what is interesting.

94
00:05:44,880 --> 00:05:48,280
Our findings did not
align with the results

95
00:05:48,280 --> 00:05:52,440
of the conventional
subgroup analysis.

96
00:05:52,440 --> 00:05:57,480
The conventional analysis, shown
on the left side of the slide,

97
00:05:57,480 --> 00:06:01,680
claimed that all
well-differentiated and all

98
00:06:01,680 --> 00:06:07,240
the differentiated patients
benefited from radiation.

99
00:06:07,240 --> 00:06:11,040
However, even in
their own forest plot,

100
00:06:11,040 --> 00:06:15,240
these findings were not
statistically significant.

101
00:06:15,240 --> 00:06:17,840
The confidence intervals
for the hazard ratios

102
00:06:17,840 --> 00:06:21,720
extended beyond one.

103
00:06:21,720 --> 00:06:24,900
In contrast, the
OPT approach, shown

104
00:06:24,900 --> 00:06:27,780
on the right side of
the slide, revealed

105
00:06:27,780 --> 00:06:32,644
a much more nuanced and
biologically plausible story.

106
00:06:32,644 --> 00:06:37,620
Among the differentiated
liposarcoma patients, only those

107
00:06:37,620 --> 00:06:42,420
without R2 rejections, meaning
complete or near-complete tumor

108
00:06:42,420 --> 00:06:47,260
removal, actually
benefited from radiation.

109
00:06:47,260 --> 00:06:51,300
Among well-differentiated
liposarcoma patients,

110
00:06:51,300 --> 00:06:54,220
benefit was seen only
in those under 60 years

111
00:06:54,220 --> 00:06:58,260
old, which is a well-known
subset with worse baseline

112
00:06:58,260 --> 00:07:01,580
prognosis.

113
00:07:01,580 --> 00:07:04,940
Let's now look at the validation
of the conventional analysis

114
00:07:04,940 --> 00:07:07,940
on the left side of the slide
and compare the findings

115
00:07:07,940 --> 00:07:10,540
on the right side of
the slide internally

116
00:07:10,540 --> 00:07:13,940
using Kaplan-Meier plots.

117
00:07:13,940 --> 00:07:17,820
The conventional analysis
on the upper left

118
00:07:17,820 --> 00:07:22,460
examined all well-differentiated
patients as a whole.

119
00:07:22,460 --> 00:07:25,020
But as shown in the
Kaplan-Meier plots,

120
00:07:25,020 --> 00:07:28,510
there was no statistically
significant benefit.

121
00:07:28,510 --> 00:07:33,230
In contrast, the OPT
analysis on the upper right

122
00:07:33,230 --> 00:07:36,510
identified a more
refined subgroup,

123
00:07:36,510 --> 00:07:40,710
well-differentiated
patients under age 60.

124
00:07:40,710 --> 00:07:42,950
And within this
group, we observed

125
00:07:42,950 --> 00:07:47,630
a statistically significant
benefit from radiation.

126
00:07:47,630 --> 00:07:50,510
This is important, not
only because it validates

127
00:07:50,510 --> 00:07:53,910
successfully the OPT method,
but it's also interesting

128
00:07:53,910 --> 00:07:58,190
because of how the
OPTs identify benefit.

129
00:07:58,190 --> 00:08:00,670
In this case, benefit
is driven not only

130
00:08:00,670 --> 00:08:06,030
by better response to treatment,
but by higher baseline risk.

131
00:08:06,030 --> 00:08:09,070
Specifically, these
younger patients

132
00:08:09,070 --> 00:08:12,310
had higher baseline
recurrence risk.

133
00:08:12,310 --> 00:08:15,390
So even if the relative
treatment effect

134
00:08:15,390 --> 00:08:20,310
was relatively similar, they
gained more in absolute terms.

135
00:08:20,310 --> 00:08:24,910
That's absolute risk
reduction in action.

136
00:08:24,910 --> 00:08:28,310
In other cases, the
benefit, or lack of it,

137
00:08:28,310 --> 00:08:31,890
has nothing to do
with baseline risk.

138
00:08:31,890 --> 00:08:36,890
It's about whether the patient
is able to respond to treatment.

139
00:08:36,890 --> 00:08:41,169
For example, as shown in the
lower left side of the figure,

140
00:08:41,169 --> 00:08:45,410
the differentiated RPS
patients with R2 rejections

141
00:08:45,410 --> 00:08:48,290
derived no benefit
from radiation.

142
00:08:48,290 --> 00:08:49,770
Why?

143
00:08:49,770 --> 00:08:52,510
Because the tumor was
not completely removed,

144
00:08:52,510 --> 00:08:56,210
so radiation
couldn't do its job.

145
00:08:56,210 --> 00:08:58,930
This is a classic case
of a treatment effect

146
00:08:58,930 --> 00:09:05,290
modifier, a factor that changes
the relative benefit of therapy.

147
00:09:05,290 --> 00:09:08,530
Look now and compare the
Kaplan-Meier plots on the lower

148
00:09:08,530 --> 00:09:11,130
left and right side.

149
00:09:11,130 --> 00:09:15,650
Baseline prognosis is
similar, but the vertical gap

150
00:09:15,650 --> 00:09:19,330
between curves differs
because the relative risk

151
00:09:19,330 --> 00:09:22,610
reduction is greater
when we exclude patients

152
00:09:22,610 --> 00:09:26,690
with R2 resection.

153
00:09:26,690 --> 00:09:31,050
So why do optimal policy trees
outperform conventional subgroup

154
00:09:31,050 --> 00:09:32,650
analysis?

155
00:09:32,650 --> 00:09:35,340
I believe the
reason is intuitive.

156
00:09:35,340 --> 00:09:39,740
Conventional subgroup analysis
looks at one factor at a time,

157
00:09:39,740 --> 00:09:42,260
like histologic subtype or age.

158
00:09:42,260 --> 00:09:45,340
But in reality, patients
differ across a constellation

159
00:09:45,340 --> 00:09:48,740
of clinical features,
not just one.

160
00:09:48,740 --> 00:09:50,220
And that's where OPTs.

161
00:09:50,220 --> 00:09:51,900
excel.

162
00:09:51,900 --> 00:09:55,500
They integrate multiple
variables simultaneously,

163
00:09:55,500 --> 00:09:59,300
allowing the algorithm to
triangulate more precisely

164
00:09:59,300 --> 00:10:03,820
which combinations of features
define subgroups with varying

165
00:10:03,820 --> 00:10:07,300
treatment response or benefit.

166
00:10:07,300 --> 00:10:11,020
This multidimensional approach
reflects the complexity

167
00:10:11,020 --> 00:10:15,060
of real patients and leads
to more accurate, clinically

168
00:10:15,060 --> 00:10:18,980
meaningful subgroup
identification.

169
00:10:18,980 --> 00:10:23,820
And perhaps just as important,
the method is objective.

170
00:10:23,820 --> 00:10:27,020
OPTs do not rely on
manually selecting

171
00:10:27,020 --> 00:10:31,140
variable combinations or
arbitrary cutoff points.

172
00:10:31,140 --> 00:10:34,380
They let the data drive
the structure, guided

173
00:10:34,380 --> 00:10:38,130
by interpretable
rule-based learning.